Related Concept: Let $S$ be a set of vectors in vector space $V$. If there exists a subset $\{\alpha_1, \alpha_2, \dots, \alpha_r\}$ such that:  
(1) $\alpha_1, \dots, \alpha_r$ are linearly independent;  
(2) Every vector in $S$ can be expressed as a linear combination of $\alpha_1, \dots, \alpha_r$;  
then this subset is called a maximal linearly independent set of $S$. All maximal linearly independent sets of $S$ have the same number of vectors, called the rank of $S$.

